{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488503"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"463"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/463"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.61,0.02,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114721"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96724"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2411"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48277"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114721"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents with a painless upper abdominal swelling which has been present for several years. He is otherwise in good health and has never had any abdominal surgery. The swelling is clearly visible when the patient lifts his head and shoulders off the bed. (Images 1, 2)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesh repair","Weight reduction","Suction lipectomy","Excision of the lump","Corset"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is the characteristic appearance of divarication of the recti, also known as rectus abdominis diastasis (RAD). RAD is the separation of the two rectus abdominis muscles. It may be congenital or acquired. The risk factors for RAD include obesity, multiparity, prior history of abdominal surgery, and connective tissue diseases. It can be easily evaluated on physical examination by asking the patient to lift up their head and the shoulders which leads to an increase in intra-abdominal pressure and contraction of the recti. The contraction of the recti becomes visible as a small bulge in the middle of the abdomen. RAD is not a hernia since there is no fascial defect. A fascial defect at this site and of this size would be very unusual. Epigastric hernias are uncommon, tend to be small and are usually evident even with the patient straining (Image). Anterior abdominal wall fascial defects tend to occur in the periumbilical area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this is not a fascial defect, there is no risk of strangulation or incarceration. For management, all that is required is to provide advice on \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight reduction and exercises\u003C/strong\u003E to strengthen the rectus abdominis muscles. It is fairly obvious from the photograph that the patient is considerably overweight. Such patients are often referred with an \u0022abdominal wall hernia\u0022 and it is important to make the correct diagnosis. Mere widening of the linea alba (ie, a band of fibrous tissue connecting the two recti) does not require any form of surgical intervention. If the degree of fascial stretching is such that there is no resolution after appropriate weight reduction and exercises, then surgical repair could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Weight reduction should be the focus of treatment for a patient with rectus divarication."],"references":["Nahabedian MY. Management Strategies for Diastasis Recti. Semin Plast Surg. 2018 Aug;32(3):147-154."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96724"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"463"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17898"},{"type":"media","id":"17899"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20324"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17898"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4849c230-1af6-4ee8-a73e-905ca535c988.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4849c230-1af6-4ee8-a73e-905ca535c988.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"17899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17899"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/51c2c583-514e-4f8f-95ed-41d2dc80e176.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/51c2c583-514e-4f8f-95ed-41d2dc80e176.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":436}},{"type":"media","id":"20324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20324"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RnE0k5eNxzHPeG3MiOD5LWWhUKNSok.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RnE0k5eNxzHPeG3MiOD5LWWhUKNSok.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96724"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T15:23:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T15:25:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114721"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up